{
  "text": "with C = C(\u03ba, \u03ba 0 ). The above inequality is established as in the proof of Lemma 23. Indeed, by linearity and symmetry we should check [CITATION_1] and (17) for L \u2202Q . To prove (15), we consider an optimal triplet (G, A, B) for (X , Y) and apply the merging property (A4) to G with the empty graph and m = 1 : we obtain a graph G \u2032\u2032 and get a triplet (G \u2032\u2032 , A, B \u222a {b}) for (X \u222a {a}, Y), where b is any point in \u2202Q. To prove (17), we now consider an optimal triplet (G, A, B) for (X \u222a {a}, Y) and move the point a to the a \u2032 in \u2202Q in order to obtain a triplet (G, A \u222a {a \u2032 }, B) for (X , Y). With (25) at hand, the statements follow from the proofs of Proposition 8 and Corollary 9.",
